WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:06.160
About 150 kilometers south of Key West,&nbsp;
Florida and 200 kilometers east of Cancun,

00:00:06.160 --> 00:00:10.000
a massive landmass splits the&nbsp;
Caribbean Sea from the Gulf of Mexico,

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.440
and marks the starting point of the 3.500&nbsp;
kilometer long island chain of the Antilles.

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:20.080
The largest island of this archipelago, and&nbsp;
17th largest Island across the whole planet

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:23.840
is called Cuba, and while its eccentric&nbsp;
leaders have had their fair share of

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:28.720
screen time in the past half millenia, the&nbsp;
island itself, with its white sandy beaches,

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:34.160
towering mogotes, tropical rainforests and&nbsp;
cactus savannahs seldom receives the spotlight.

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:38.320
Therefore, in this video we will take a closer&nbsp;
look at the many mountain ranges scattered around

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:43.840
the islands, the 6 ecoregions which make up the&nbsp;
rolling hills and fertile plains in between them,

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:49.600
and the mosaic of kays, mangroves and&nbsp;
coral reefs which surround the main island.

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:53.600
Chapter 1: The Mountains
At first glance, the island

00:00:53.600 --> 00:00:59.040
of Cuba appears like a flat stretch, drawn&nbsp;
between the two seas, but the monotonous plains

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:04.880
of central Cuba are only half the truth.
With an age of over 250 million years,

00:01:04.880 --> 00:01:09.120
the island is clearly not shaped by recent&nbsp;
tectonic activity, but several mountain ranges

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:14.960
have stood the test of time, and remind us to this&nbsp;
date, what immense forces have shaped this island.

00:01:14.960 --> 00:01:19.200
A total of 4 isolated mountain ranges&nbsp;
are standing above the largely flat and

00:01:19.200 --> 00:01:24.560
fertile plains, turning Cubas homogenic&nbsp;
biota into a diverse tropical landscape,

00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:28.720
which fosters endemism across&nbsp;
many species of flora and fauna.

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:32.960
The largest of these mountainous areas&nbsp;
are the Nipe-Sagua-Baracoa Mountains,

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:37.760
which cover the eastern tip of the island,&nbsp;
just north of the infamous Guantanamo Bay.

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:40.880
The 3 ranges which are smoothly&nbsp;
transitioning between each other,

00:01:40.880 --> 00:01:45.280
are receiving much of the moist air coming from&nbsp;
the Atlantic Ocean, whose clouds are emptying

00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:51.120
themselves on the north eastern slopes. With&nbsp;
an annual precipitation of 2700 mm per year,

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:55.840
it is one of the most precipitous regions of&nbsp;
Central America, and despite the thin soil,

00:01:55.840 --> 00:02:00.080
a prosperous tropical rainforest has&nbsp;
developed on the slopes of these mountains.

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:03.120
Pico Cristal, the highest&nbsp;
point of the mountain range,

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:08.000
rises to an elevation of 1,300 meters above&nbsp;
the sea level but it pales in comparison to

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:13.760
its southern neighbor. Stretching along Cuba's&nbsp;
southeastern coastline for 140 kilometers,

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:19.680
the Sierra Maestra mountains boast Pico&nbsp;
Turquino, which with 1970 meters is

00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:24.480
the island's tallest peak and one of the&nbsp;
highest summits in the Greater Antilles.

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:28.000
Standing as a rainforest covered&nbsp;
tower over the Caribbean Sea,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
this summit is actually the only place&nbsp;
in Cuba where snowfall has been recorded,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.400
with the winter of 1900 bringing&nbsp;
this peculiarity into the tropics.

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:41.520
The area in and around Pico Turquino has been a&nbsp;
hotspot for coffee cultivation since the mid 17th

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:46.240
century, and this practice, which has been&nbsp;
started by Spanish and French Colonialists,

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:51.760
has continued to this date, with 92% of Cuba’s&nbsp;
coffee coming from the Sierra Maestra Mountains.

00:02:51.760 --> 00:02:55.760
Each of the Cuban mountain ranges has one&nbsp;
particular crop which grows exceptionally

00:02:55.760 --> 00:03:00.880
well there. The central Escambray Mountains for&nbsp;
example, have been dominated by the cultivation

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:05.280
of sugarcane, with the mountain's southern&nbsp;
slope having been the heart of the global

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:11.120
sugar industry. Since this industry however&nbsp;
was built through the blood of 30.000 slaves,

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:15.520
not much of this industry is left today,&nbsp;
and a large UNESCO heritage site covering

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:20.320
the terraced fields and old sugar mills,&nbsp;
reminds us of this dark part of history.

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:25.040
Far on the western side of Cuba, the traditional&nbsp;
industry has persisted though, with many

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:30.400
international connoisseurs worshipping what mother&nbsp;
nature is giving us here. Just the right levels of

00:03:30.400 --> 00:03:35.920
precipitation, sunlight and temperature, together&nbsp;
with a soil that is rich in nitrates, calcium and

00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:41.920
manganese, result in the leaves of the tobacco&nbsp;
plant here being hailed as the best in the world.

00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:46.160
Between these far apart mountain ranges,&nbsp;
flat valleys are home to the rest of the

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:51.440
Cuban agriculture, but despite this heavy human&nbsp;
impact on the landscape, several unique regions

00:03:51.440 --> 00:03:55.280
still persists, which couldn't be more&nbsp;
different from each other, bringing us to

00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:59.280
Chapter 2: The Ecoregions
According to the Köppen climate

00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:04.240
classification, which is a system commonly used&nbsp;
to subdivide the world into different climatic

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:09.200
zones and subzones, nearly the entirety&nbsp;
of Cuba is considered tropical Savannah,

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:13.280
with only the north eastern and western&nbsp;
coastal zones behind the mountains being

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:17.040
classified as tropical rainforest.
This however has not held back

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:20.960
the ecoregions from developing and&nbsp;
sprawling in many different varieties.&nbsp;

00:04:20.960 --> 00:04:25.520
The four mountain ranges that we have discussed&nbsp;
already are largely covered with cuban moist,

00:04:25.520 --> 00:04:29.760
dry and pine forest ecoregions, which all&nbsp;
have their unique characteristics based on

00:04:29.760 --> 00:04:34.160
the fertility and moisture retention ability of&nbsp;
the soil, whether they have a distinctive dry

00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:38.720
and wet seasons, and by the dominant tree&nbsp;
type like broadleaf, or deciduous trees.

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:42.640
Moving closer to the coast, the more&nbsp;
peculiar ecoregions start to emerge,

00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:47.280
with the southern coastline under the Nipe
Sagua Baracoa Mountains coming straight out of an

00:04:47.280 --> 00:04:52.560
alien planet. Since the rain shadow effect&nbsp;
creates extreme aridity, the precipitation

00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:58.480
rate here is the lowest anywhere in Cuba, which&nbsp;
has created the so-called Cuban Cactus Shrub.

00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:02.640
Succulent plants, meaning plants with the&nbsp;
ability to store large amounts of water,

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:07.520
are populating the skeletal limestone&nbsp;
soil and despite the less than 800mm

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:12.720
of annual precipitation, with dry periods&nbsp;
ranging between 9 and 11 months per year,

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:16.400
they have formed the basis of&nbsp;
an extraordinary ecosystem.

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:22.400
The Cuban Rock Iguana, the Pigmy Eleuth and flower&nbsp;
bats have adjusted to this harsh environment,

00:05:22.400 --> 00:05:26.960
but economic incentives are putting this&nbsp;
environment at risk, slowly replacing the endemic

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:32.960
thorny bushes with Sisal, a plant cultivated&nbsp;
for its stiff fibres used in rope manufacturing.

00:05:32.960 --> 00:05:37.360
Further down the coast to the west, the&nbsp;
moisture suddenly becomes abundant, creating

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:42.720
the biological opposite of the cactus shrublands.&nbsp;
Starting from the shoreline of the Bay of Pigs,

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:47.920
which also had its entry in the history books in&nbsp;
the last century, the vast Zapata swamp stretches

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:53.280
for over 100 kilometers and is the largest&nbsp;
representative of the Cuban Wetland Ecoregion.

00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:58.640
Spanning 4% of Cuba’s territory, this&nbsp;
vast swamp features caves, sinkholes,

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:03.040
depressions, and floodplains that form a&nbsp;
dynamic hydrographic network of marshes,

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:08.000
freshwater lagoons, and transition zones&nbsp;
leading to the Caribbean Sea. Daily tidal

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.480
movements breathe life into this ecosystem&nbsp;
by pushing water masses through the swamp,

00:06:12.480 --> 00:06:16.400
and seasonal floods regularly cover the&nbsp;
savannah of the hinterland prompting the

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:20.240
migration of hundreds of thousands&nbsp;
birds to depart from these wetlands.

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:25.600
Within the swamps marine ecosystem, sharks,&nbsp;
crocodiles and manatees are feeding on the

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:29.920
abundance of fish and vegetation, and the&nbsp;
most peculiar of birds is soaring through

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:36.000
the dense flora. At 1.6 grams and with&nbsp;
wing flaps of up to 80 times per second,

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:41.360
the bee hummingbird is rushing from flower to&nbsp;
flower, and keeping the whole ecosystem running.

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:45.760
Much of the remaining coastline of Cuba&nbsp;
is covered by the 6th and final ecoregion,

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:51.760
called the mangrove. Mangroves cover 5.1% of&nbsp;
Cuba’s land area—accounting for 20% of its

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:56.960
remaining forest and protecting over half its&nbsp;
coastline from natural disasters. Particularly

00:06:56.960 --> 00:07:01.680
the southern coast is prone to hurricanes and&nbsp;
storm surges, which are being slowed down by

00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:05.760
the kilometer deep network of Mangrove&nbsp;
roots, which hold everything in place.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:09.760
While being an important part of the islands&nbsp;
sea defence turing times of distress from

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:14.320
mother nature, it also plays a vital role in&nbsp;
balancing the mass balance of the ecoregion,

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:19.280
since sediments from the receding tidal swells&nbsp;
are being trapped in the root network, slowing

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:24.720
down coastal erosion and readjusting the sea&nbsp;
bed level in light of the global sea level rise.

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:28.480
As a harbour of life for all sorts&nbsp;
of species, the mangroves are the

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:32.960
most protected habitat of Cuba, and not just&nbsp;
cover large swaths of the main island's coast,

00:07:32.960 --> 00:07:37.120
but also many of the surrounding keys and&nbsp;
islets. While the country of Cuba is often

00:07:37.120 --> 00:07:41.600
only associated with its main island, there are&nbsp;
actually thousands of these smaller islands,

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:46.720
making Cuba a massive archipelago in itself&nbsp;
and bringing us to the third and final chapter

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:50.960
Chapter 3: The greater Archipelago
Across its entire territory,

00:07:50.960 --> 00:07:56.880
the country of Cuba consists of a staggering&nbsp;
4195 islands, which are grouped into 4

00:07:56.880 --> 00:08:01.680
archipelagos off the northern and southern&nbsp;
coastline in the shallow nearshore areas.

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:06.960
The archipelago with the most islands is located&nbsp;
along the central northern coast and accounts for

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:12.960
2500 islands along its 450 kilometer extent. Many&nbsp;
of the larger islands here are connected through

00:08:12.960 --> 00:08:18.320
a road network consisting of long causeways which&nbsp;
were constructed at the end of the last century,

00:08:18.320 --> 00:08:23.440
now allowing for the development of luxury&nbsp;
beach resorts on the white sandy beaches.

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:28.240
The eastern and western extends of this&nbsp;
archipelago however are virtually untouched,

00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:33.120
harbouring much of the Cuban mangrove forests&nbsp;
and wetlands. These islands are much younger

00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:38.480
than the main island and often just consist of a&nbsp;
large pile of sand which sticks out of the sea.

00:08:38.480 --> 00:08:44.320
Their existence today is thanks to thousands&nbsp;
of former coral reefs, which teemed the seabed

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:50.320
around 130.000 years ago, during a time when the&nbsp;
sea level was much higher than today. Upon their

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:55.920
death, the coral skeleton trapped free flowing&nbsp;
sediments from the ocean currents, which have then

00:08:55.920 --> 00:09:01.920
been exposed by the roughly 25m of sea level&nbsp;
drop that earth has experienced since then.

00:09:01.920 --> 00:09:05.760
Today, these keys are threatened by&nbsp;
the very mechanic that created them,

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:09.840
with significant erosion from wind&nbsp;
and water removing the sand, and the

00:09:09.840 --> 00:09:14.480
rising sea level threatening to drown them
again. Luckily, the mangroves are slowing

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:20.320
these developments but it is uncertain exactly&nbsp;
how long they will remain to be appreciated.

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:24.080
On the other side of the Cuban main&nbsp;
island lie the Queen's Gardens,

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:29.360
named by Christopher Columbus in honor of Spain’s&nbsp;
queen upon his sighting. Known as the "Galapagos

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:34.480
of the Caribbean," this archipelago boasts some&nbsp;
of Cuba’s most pristine underwater landscapes,

00:09:34.480 --> 00:09:39.680
with vibrant coral reefs teeming with groupers,&nbsp;
reef sharks, and American crocodiles that attract

00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:44.240
divers and snorkelers from all over the&nbsp;
world. Designated as a nature reserve,

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:49.600
these islands have no permanent inhabitants,&nbsp;
and strict regulations on tourism and fishing

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:54.000
ensure their preservation. In recent decades,&nbsp;
fishing has actually been banned outright

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.560
within the parks boundaries, which has since&nbsp;
then turned the marine ecosystem into a fish

00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:02.960
spawning machine, benefitting not just the&nbsp;
biodiversity, but also the fishing industry.

00:10:02.960 --> 00:10:06.160
The catch in the deeper waters has&nbsp;
increased dramatically since the

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:09.920
adaptation of this policy, leading&nbsp;
to fisherman and conservationists

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:13.840
now pulling on the same rope,&nbsp;
to preserve this wilderness.

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:19.200
180 kilometers west of these underwater worlds,&nbsp;
the Canarreos Archipelago starts stretching for

00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:25.760
300 kilometers around the Zapata Swamp, and among&nbsp;
the 350 islands of this archipelago, Cuba's second

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:31.600
largest island lies right in the middle of it
The Isle of Youth as it was named by Fidel Castro,

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:36.980
was formerly known as the Isle of Pines, which&nbsp;
today best describes its vegetation. The low

00:10:36.980 --> 00:10:41.680
lying ridges of the north are nearly completely&nbsp;
covered in Caribbean pine, while the southern

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:46.880
plains are covered in a massive swamp, similar&nbsp;
to the Zapata Swamp of the main island, housing

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:52.800
an incredible hydrological network and giving a&nbsp;
home to hundreds of thousands of migratory birds.

00:10:52.800 --> 00:10:58.240
All in all, Cuba has an astounding geographical&nbsp;
diversity along its thin latitudinal extent,

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:02.880
covering misty mountains, idyllic&nbsp;
beaches, fertile plains and slopes,

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:06.560
and some of the most interesting and&nbsp;
best preserved wetlands in the world.

00:11:06.560 --> 00:11:11.120
I hope you have learned something new on this&nbsp;
journey across the island of Cuba. If you want to

00:11:11.120 --> 00:11:15.680
get notified when the next mini-documentary comes&nbsp;
out, you can subscribe. And if you want to support

00:11:15.680 --> 00:11:20.160
the channel even more, you can now also leave a&nbsp;
small donation at my Buy Me a Coffee Page with

00:11:20.160 --> 00:11:26.560
the link in the middle of the screen or in the&nbsp;
description. See you in the next video, cheers.

